<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence for Transport Select Committee – Follow-up Inquiry into Cycle Safety</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (CYS0040)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><hr style="height:2px; text-align:center; width:100%" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="a1"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whether c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ycling is safe, particularly in towns and cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What central and local Government could do more to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improve cycling safety. Ideas could include better training and advice for drivers and cyclists, better enforcement of the law applying to drivers and cyclists, and better vehicle and road infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whether it would be desirable and feasible to segr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egate cyclists from other road users, including, for example, by prohibiting HGVs from ente</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ring city centres at peak hours?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The safety of cyclists is important to the Departmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t, as are all casualties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s highways. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As more and more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people take up cycling we are absolutely determined to improve their safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; whether this is achieved through training, awareness and/or through infrastructure. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> made significant investment into cycling. Investing almost double that spent in the last five years of the previous administration. We have particularly focused on making it safer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and easier for people to cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by: </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improving links between cycle networks;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">making safety improvements at junctions; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing major investment in cycling in 8 cities across the country, to create a step change in cycling provision in those places. </span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department has worked with a wide range of cycling stakeholders, includi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng other Government departments, local authorities, police, cycle interest groups and other relevant stakeholders. These stakeholders are represented on one or more groups that look at a variety of areas, such as safety, justice, cycle-rail and cycle proof</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing roads. The groups assist and inform the Department in the delivery of new policies and changes to existing regulations to enable people to cycle more safely and more often. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cycling casualty statistics</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Number of cycling casualties in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> (excluding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">)</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> casualty from cycling is unwelcome; however the statistics show that cycling is not inherently unsafe. Whilst more can be done to improve safety, it is reasonable to say that for the majority of cyclists travelling by bicycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is safe in our urban areas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The number of cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">casualtie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s is dependent on a range of factors – for example, the underlying rate of cycling within the population, or “external” factors such as the weather – meaning that there is no single, simple soluti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A summary of the most recent statistics follows.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012 there were 14 fatalities and 673 KSIs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (that equates to 35 fatalities per billion miles cycled and 1,683 KSIs per billion miles cycled). In the rest of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these figures were 91 fat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alities (33 / billion miles) and 2,407 (860 / billion miles).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The total number of reported pedal cycle casualties (all severities) decreased by 1% to 19,091 from 2011 to 2012. The 2012 total is 16 per cent higher than the 2005-09 average.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">total of 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">05</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pedal cyclists were killed in reported road accidents in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent lower than the 2005-2009 average. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">What has affected the trends</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2012 was an unusually wet year – the second wettest on record – which is likely to have dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">couraged people from using the road, thereby lowering the number of casualties. Pedal cyclists are particularly likely to be sensitive to such abnormal weather, by the very nature of how exposed they are to the elements; we may have expected higher pedal c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yclist casualty figures in the absence of these high levels of rainfall.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further work is being undertaken in order to allow us to better understand the effects weather has on road casualty numbers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The overall casualty trend is likely to be influenced by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the changes in pedal cycle traffic volumes. Although the number of pedal cycle KSI casualties has been increasing since 2004, pedal cycle traffic has also been on a general increase. Road traffic estimates have shown gradual increases in the distance cycl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Great Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with a 1.2 per cent rise between 2011 and 2012 to 3.1 billion vehicle miles. This figure is over 12 per cent higher than the 2005-09 average.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Pedal cycle traffic is relatively difficult to measure, compared to motor vehicle traffic. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he National Travel Survey suggests that the growth in pedal cycle traffic over this period is actually closer to 23 per cent. We intend to carry out more work to assess the best way to estimate pedal cycle distance travelled.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Cycle casualties in urban are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">as</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There were 14 pedal cyclist fatalities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2012, two fewer than the previous year. Pedal cyclists are over represented in terms of KSI casualties in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; there were 673 pedal cycle KSI casualties in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2012, which is 38 per cent highe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r than the 2005-09 average. This represents 20 per cent of all pedal cycle KSIs, whereas London accounts for 13 per cent of pedal cycle traffic in Great Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">note </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as discussed in point 10, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are difficulties in accurately measuring pedal cycle traf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A total of 54 pedal cyclists were killed in road accidents in urban areas in 2012. This is two more than in 2011; however this is 19 per cent lower than the 2005-09 average.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Funding for cycling</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the life of this Parliament, £278m of Government funds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been committed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">towards cycling (£375m with match funding). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This funding has been used to develop better and safer infrastructure, provide training and to cities in delivering an increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the number of people cycling. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This was spent on:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£94m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to increase cycling in cities and national parks (with a further £54m of match funding)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£20m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to deliver safer junctions outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (with a further £20m of match funding)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£14.5m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a major enabler towards doubling the amount of cycle parking at rail stations (with a further £6m of match funding)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£15.5m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to provide more safe cycle links between communities, that also support walking (with a further £15m of match funding)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£15m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TfL for their programme to improve junction safety in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£44m </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Bikeability cycle training</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£13m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Links to Schools programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, 94 out of 96 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cal Sustainable Transport Fund </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">projects include cycling as an element in their delivery pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ogrammes; these 94 projects receive a total of £535m of DfT funding. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2013/14, through the Integrated Transport Block, we are providing £320m to local authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (outside of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) for small transport improvement schemes. This includes: ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ad safety schemes, bus priority schemes, and walking and cycling schemes.  This funding is not ring fenced and offers local authorities the freedom to develop and implement solutions which best suit their localities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Training</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department recognises </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that there is value in training cyclists to ride saf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ely and confidently on the road;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this is achieved through the Bikeability programme.  Bikeability is underpinned by the National Standard for cycle training.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Standard is built upon similar pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inciples to training for motorcycle riders and car drivers, teaching the importance of assessing the likely risks faced by road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">users. There are three National Standard levels with a series of outcomes for each that a trainee must demonstrate.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Departm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent for Transport provides funding to Local Highway Authorities and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Games</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Organiser</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Host</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the delivery of Bikeability training to children between school years 5 – 9 (ages 9-14). 24 million is available between April 2013 and March 2015 w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hich will allow a minimum of 600,000 children to be trained (based on a maximum contribution of £40 per head) to levels 1&amp; 2 combined, Level 2 and/or Level 3 (Level 2 is aimed at school years 5 – 7 and Level 3 is aimed at school years 7 – 9). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.05pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bikeability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not only for children.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a range of training available to suit all requirements from the complete beginner wanting to boost their confidence to those wanting to develop more advanced skills. The Bikeability website contains further information f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or those wishing to find a suitable cycle training provider. Some local authorities also provide free or subsidised adult cycle training.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Driving standards</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Both the Driving Standards Agency’s (DSA) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">national driver and rider training standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which describes the skills, knowledge and understanding needed to be a safe and responsible driving instructor, and its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">national standard for driving cars,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which sets out what the DSA believes is needed to be a safe and responsible driver, are very clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about the importance of the need for drivers and motorcyclists to be aware of vulnerable road users like cyclists. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Two of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s largest driving schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– the AA and BSM –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">teach specific modules of cycle safety to their pupils.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The modules have been c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reated with input from cyclists.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The driving test, both the theory and the practical tests assess a candidate’s awareness of, and knowledge of how to deal appropriately with, vulnerable road users.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The theory test contains specific questions to assess </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a candidate’s awareness of cyclists and whilst the DSA cannot guarantee that a practical test candidate will encounter a cyclist during their test, many of its test routes include roads with cycle lanes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The independent driving section of the practical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">test gives the candidate the opportunity to demonstrate how they can read the road and deal with hazards and other road users as if driving unaccompanied.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is designed to assess a candidate’s abili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty while making decisions on their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> own; a candidate who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cannot do this and does not show awareness of, and consideration for, other road users will not pass the test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DSA produces publications about driver and rider safety, dealing with other road users, developing awareness and anticipation for the actions of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other road users.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As well as being used as training material, the publications can also be used as an ongoing reference post-test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">everal new CPC (Certificate of Professional Competence) courses for lorry drivers are now taking cyclists into account, and may even require the driver to experience being a cyclist. In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">initiatives such as TfL’s “Exchanging Places” events, where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one can sit in a lorry cab and watch for a police cyclist riding up the left side of the vehicle, provide opportunities for educating both drivers and cyclists as to the dangers arising at junctions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Awareness </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On 21 October 2013 Robert Goodwill launched</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a new THINK! cyclist campaign, targeting Leeds, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cambridge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This builds on last year’s launch of the ‘THINK CYCLIST’ “Let’s Look Out For Each Other” campaign </span><a href="http://think.direct.gov.uk/cycling.html"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://th</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ink.direc</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">.gov.</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">u</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">k/cycling.html</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This was the first time a THINK! (road safety) campaign has been aimed at adult cyclists. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, THINK! also offers guidance on cycling as part of our education materials:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycle Safety Advice for Parents of Children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> aged 5 to 7</span><br /><a href="http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/early-years-and-primary/parents/5-to-7s/cycle-safety/"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/early-years-and-primary/parents/5-to-7s/cycle-safety/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycle Safety Advice for Parents of Children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aged 7 to 11</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><a href="http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/early-years-and-primary/parents/7-to-11s/cycle-safety/"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/early-years-and-primary/parents/7-to-11s/cycle-safety/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycle Safety Advice for Parents of Childre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n aged 12+</span><br /><a href="http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/secondary/parents/cycle-safety/"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://think.direct.gov.uk/education/secondary/parents/cycle-safety/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cycle safety advice in Tales of the Road can be found at:</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://talesoftheroad.direct.gov.uk/cycling-safety.php"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://talesoftheroad.direct.gov.uk/cycling-safety.php</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Road Infrastructure </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Decisions on how best to provide for cyclists on local roads are matters for the local authority – not only do they have a duty to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">balance the needs of all road users when considering how to design and manage their road networks, but they also have a detailed understanding of their roads.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our guidance in Local Transport Note 2/08: Cycle Infrastructure Design is comprehensive and allo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ws councils to design good, safe schemes within current legislation. It already includes most of the measures highlighted as good practice by, for example, the All Party Parliamentary Cycling Group, and British Cycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Appropriate training of designers a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd engineers is essential to the delivery of high quality cycling infrastructure. We believe that this is a key area to be addressed and have had initial discussions with professional bodies such as the Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the Institution of Highway Engineers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">said that we will consider endorsing guidance currently being drafted by Transport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the Welsh Government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have already done a lot to help local councils provide for cyclists. Even before the Prime Minister’s announcement on 12 August of funding for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and the commitments to cycle proof the strategic road network, we made a large number of chang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2011 we made considerable amendments to traffic signing to allow a range of new measures, for example: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contraflow cycling, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new cycle route signing and branding, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new designs of Advanced Stop Lines, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use of trixi mirrors, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater flexibility for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">installing 20mph zones.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In October 2012 TfL commissioned TRL to trial measures including low level mini signals, new roundabout designs and new ways of helping cyclists turn right at traffic lights. We have been working closely with them on this, and are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on both working and steering groups for the trials.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have also given Cambridgeshire County Council permission to trial an ‘early start’ signal for cyclists, as an alternative way of allowing cyclists priori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty at traffic lights. Transport for Greater Man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chester is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> looking at a similar scheme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are working on delivering even more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changes;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by revising the Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions (TSRGD). These changes have been developed in conjunction with cycling stakeholders over the last five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> years. Measures being considered include:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Removing the requirement for a lead-in lane for cyclists at advanced stop lines, making it easier for highway authorities to install advanced stop lines at junctions; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New traffic lights to give cyclists a head </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">start at junctions;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Options for joint crossings for use by both pedestrians and cyclists;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Options for bigger cycle boxes (advanced stop lines), to accommodate the growth in cycling, and to make it safer for cyclists at junctions;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Removing the requirement f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or Traffic Orders for mandatory cycle lanes and exemptions for cyclists, such as ‘no right turn except cycles’. This will make it easier for local authorities to install cycle facilities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are now focused on working with lawyers to draft the new regulations. We expect these to go out for public consultation in Spring 2014, with the aim of bringing them into force by April 2015. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department has established a new group (the Cycle Proof</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing working group) under the remit of the Cycle Stakeholder Forum to:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Help local authorities share good practice, knowledge and experience on the engineering and traffic management solutions already available to address common challenges to making roads m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore cycle-friendly;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investigate opportunities for local government collaboration in the preparation and testing of new engineering and traffic management solutions; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Help local authorities identify how best to involve cyclists themselves in identifying </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the right solutions to local challenges</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Enforcement</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highway Code provides clear advice to drivers to take extra care when sharing the road with more vulnerable road users, such as cyclists.  It advises drivers to watch out for cyclists at junctions, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o check mirrors for blind spots and to give cyclists plenty of room. Drivers can be prosecuted for careless or dangerous driving offences if their behaviour warrants such action.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department has created a new criminal offence of causing serious injury by dangerous driving in the Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act which carries a maximum prison sentence of 5 years.  This offence will ensure that dangerous driver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s will be punished appropriately when their actions have serious consequences.  For the vast majority of dangerous driving cases, the maximum penalty of 2 years' imprisonment provides the courts with sufficient and proportionate powers to punish offenders.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fixed penalty notice for careless driving offences is aimed at all aspects of careless driving.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Careless driving puts lives at risk and is a major source of concern and irritation for law-abiding motorists.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The penalty notice allows the police gre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ater flexibility when dealing with careless driving offences, including offering educational training as an alternative to an endorsement, where this is considered appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Like all road users, cyclists have a duty to behave in a safe and responsible manner, and this is reflected in the Highway Code's rules for cyclists which can be found at </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/rules-for-cyclists-59-to-82"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/rules-</span><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">for-cyclists-59-to-82</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Road Traffic Act 1991 created cycling offences parallel to those of careless and dangerous driving. The maximum fines are currently £1,000 for careless cycling and £2,500 for dangerous cycling. The enforcement of cycling of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fences is an operational matter for individual chief officers of police. We support any action taken by the police to deter and reduce the number of cycling offences.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Vehicle design</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proportion of cycling fatalities reported involving HGVs makes it in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evitable that we need to consider vehicle design. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Technical regulations to improve the driver’s view around their HGV have been agreed at the UN-ECE in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Geneva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but still require implementation in the European Union. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We anticipate these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> changes will apply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to new vehicle types from 30 June 2014 once agreement has been reached in the EU.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most new goods vehicles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have to comply with minimum requirements on the fitting of sideguards. However, from 29 October 2014, all new goods vehicles will have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comply with revised European rules, which permit fewer exemptions than the current domestic legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New technology has an important role to play in helping to improve the safety of all road users. We fully support the voluntary initiatives by some construction companies to fit their vehicles with additional safety devices including sensors and cameras bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t at this time we are not in a position to support mandatory fitment of proximity sensors in HGVs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The mandatory introduction of any new vehicle technology would need to be agreed at EU level, it would require evidence that the technology is reliable an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d robust, and that the systems will deliver the expected benefit rather than simply imposing additional cost that could otherwise support more effective safety measures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst basic proximity sensors are widely available as parking aids, they might not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be capable of reliably detecting cyclists along the full length of an HGV. To be effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sensors must be robust (e.g. not react to roadside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> furniture or pedestrians on the pavement)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as repeated false warnings might actually distract drivers or lead them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to turn the system off. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sensor technology is developing rapidly and some advanced systems now combine input from both sensors and cameras to improve the detection capability. These systems are typically designed to detect pedestrians and are available o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n some top-of-the-range cars. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As this technology matures we would expect systems to become more affordable and to offer real opportunities to mitigate the type of accid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent involving cyclists and HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However until sensors can distinguish between cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sts, pedestrians passing on the pavement and railings or other street furniture, there are real risks that they will be simply switched off or ignored. In September 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a new dedicated Industrial HGV Task Force for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was launched</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The role of the Ta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sk Force will be to raise awareness of safety requirements for HGVs and drivers, and to take targeted enforcement action against the small minority of potentially dangerous operators, drivers and vehicles. The enforcement has been intelligence-led and has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resulted in a high detection rate of violations being detected and brought to book. To date, over 500 lorries have been checked and more than half were issued with prohibition notices.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Segregation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The segregation of cyclists can bring some safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefits; however, separating cyclists from other traffic will not always be better for cyclists, as if implemented inappropriately it can increase the potential for conflict between cycles and motor vehicles at intersections with the road network.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t we encourage segregation alongside high speed roads, in urban environments space is often at a premium. Providing a broad, high quality cycle route segregated from motor traffic in these circumstances might be desirable but in many cases it is not always</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practicable</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important that each proposal to improve conditions for cyclists is considered in relation to the prevailing circumstances and not with a presumption that removing cyclists from the carriageway is always a good thing. This is why these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decisions are best made by local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department’s guidance, Local Transport Note 2/08 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cycle Infrastructure Design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, discusses this approach in greater detail. </span><a href="http://assets.dft.gov.uk/publications/local-transport-notes/ltn-2-08.pdf"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://assets.dft.gov.uk/publications/local-transport-notes/ltn-2-08.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Separating cyclists from other traffic can be particularly difficult in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our cities where the demands on space are considerable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LTN 2/08 already does recommend separating cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sts from other traffic, but not generally in urban situations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prohibiting HGVs during peak hours</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local traffic authorities have powers under Sections 1 &amp; 2 of the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984, to make Traffic Regulation Orders (TROs) designed to reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ulate, restrict or prohibit the use of a road or any part of the width of a road by vehicular traffic or pedestrians for a wide range of safety and environmental reasons.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These powers can be used to exclude HGVs either generally or at specified times fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om roads for which they are considered to be unsuitable, either because of the risk of damage to the road or neighbouring buildings, or on general environmental grounds – but due account must be given to the availability of alternative routes.  These restr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ictions should be indicated by suitable signs as set by the Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions 2002, or otherwise authorised by the Secretary of State. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is up to the local authority to balance the need for restrictions against their impac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t on the prohibition on residents, the local economy and environmental factors. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>